&nbsp;</span><b style=\"font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 19.1875px;\">database</b><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19.1875px;\">&nbsp;is an organized collection of data. The data is typically organized to model relevant aspects of reality (for example, the availability of rooms in hotels), in a way that supports processes requiring this information (for example, finding a hotel with vacancies).</span><br>','2013-04-01 08:52:58','db'),(17,7,'<ul><li><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 255);\"></span><br></li></ul><span style=\"font-family: monospace;\">I\r\nhave been mostly working in the area of WDM optical networks which are\r\nwidely deployed in the core of the Internet. There&nbsp;are many issues\r\nyet to be resolved&nbsp;in the core networks although the technology has been\r\nquite mature in this area for the past one&nbsp;decade.\r\nThis is due to lack of consensus among different OEM vendors on the issue of\r\nstandardization of architectures and protocols. The vision of deploying\r\na reconfigurable, robust, optical network at the core is plagued by\r\nlack of mature cost-effective solutions for optical logic processing and\r\nbuffering. An intermediate solution proposed by some researchers\r\ntowards the realization of bufferless optical&nbsp;core network, is the\r\noptical burst switched network which uses a separate&nbsp;plane to\r\nprocess the control information while retaining the optical data flow.\r\nHowever, due to &nbsp;the bufferless nature of the core nodes and bursty\r\ntraffic, resolving contention and providing guaranteed delivery become\r\nmajor issues of research. Due to lack of consensus on the\r\narchitecture and protocols for bufferless networks and also due to the\r\nrandom nature of contention losses, this paradigm of switching is\r\nlosing its ground.<br></span><span style=\"font-family: monospace;\"><br>During my Ph.D I have\r\nfocused largely on the design of efficient mechanisms to estimate,\r\nunderstand and analyze the contention losses in bufferless optical networks. &nbsp;One of\r\nthe foremost conclusion in the work was that any mechanism to measure\r\nor control the losses in bufferless networks must be purely\r\nnon-invasive and use no additional support from the core nodes\r\nwhich would require complex functionalities to be placed at the core.\r\nTechniques from the field of network tomography are very effective in estimation of various metrics in\r\nthe network. However, there is a need for new theoretical models to\r\ncharacterize the traffic and behaviour of\r\nbufferless networks before the existing techniques can be used.\r\n&nbsp;The characteristics of traffic in optical burst switching\r\nnetworks are not very widely understood and any\r\ntechniques for congestion control or resource allocation in these\r\nnetworks need to be understood by accurate mathematical analysis.\r\n&nbsp;Another major conclusion from the earlier work is that the losses in\r\nnetworks without buffers or even with very small buffers show\r\nsignificant variation in the distributions over time and with\r\nvarying topology and input traffic conditions. In such situations, to\r\naccurately differentiate congestion from temporary random losses plays\r\na significant role in the design of congestion control mechanisms. Apart from this, we\r\nhave also seen that many of the existing techniques for analyzing\r\nnetworks with queues fail in case of bufferless highspeed networks.\r\nAlthough, researchers use models from circuit switched telephone\r\nnetworks to approximately characterize optical networks, they do not yield\r\naccurate results in many situations. <br><br>Recently, some\r\nresearchers&nbsp;proposed reducing the buffers at the core routers by a\r\nlarge factor to save energy consumption. The reduction in buffer size\r\nto just a few&nbsp;packets have also shown to yield good link\r\nutilizations subject to certain conditions. This research is&nbsp;also\r\nseen to be advantageous in deployment of optical packet switching at the core Internet which is the ultimate vision in\r\nthe area of highspeed networks. There has been wide-spread debate over\r\nthe reduction in the buffer size to just a few packets, supported\r\nwith&nbsp;simulations and experimental results that favour and oppose\r\nthe tiny-buffer networks. I am currently focused on investigating\r\nvarious aspects\r\n&nbsp;of congestion control and resource management in tiny-buffer\r\nhighspeed networks. I am looking at theoretical models to characterize\r\nthe traffic in such networks as well\r\nas devising new architectures and protocols to operate highspeed\r\nnetworks with tiny or no buffers. </span>','2013-04-12 20:24:58','highspeed networks'),(16,8,'<pre>1. All the components should be put in one folder and create a\r\ntar.tgz/zip/7z file.\r\n\r\n2. All the installations, creation of the database, population of the\r\ndatabased should be automatic through a scripting file\r\n   - a shell/perl/python should be written to create the required database\r\nand related tables.\r\n   - The database should be populated through the script.\r\n   - We will simply run the scrpt to create your database and populate it.\r\nIf there is no such script to ceate and install, then your project is\r\nnot deployable and hence incomplete.\r\n\r\n3. There should be a readme or installation file. It should content every\r\ndetails of your installation in step-by-step format. We will just follow\r\nthe steps given in the readme file. After following the steps, if your\r\napplication does not work, your project is incomplete. This file should\r\nhave\r\n   - OS required\r\n   - Additional tools required\r\n   --- If you are using a tool, which is not publicly available, you\r\nshould supply it to us.\r\n   --- All the source/URL of these tools should be clearly cited.\r\n   --- Installation procedure of these tools should be clearly mentioned.\r\n   - All other installation steps\r\n\r\n4. Your submission should have a user\'s manual. It should explain  every\r\ndetails of HOT-TO-USE of your application\r\n\r\n5. If you want to host your application for campus usage, you can kindly\r\nindicate in your submission mail. I will try to server space. However,\r\nthis option does not carry and extra credit.\r\n\r\n6. A brief report of Your Database design.\r\n</pre>','2013-04-12 20:34:11','how to submit your project');
